I used the run_cpu.sh and run_gpu.sh files with srun.
--cpus-per-task=4 for the cpu run
The commands used for the gpu version is from this labs readme, cpu is from lab2 (and so is the solution)

Conclusion is that gpu is very fast. Also the scaling is different.
With cpu, the time increase is always larger than the size increase squared, which makes sense, since increasing the 2D size by 4 increases the operation count by 4*4=16.
However, the time increase with gpu is a lot smaller compared to the size increase, and not consistent (1.3 for x4, 2.9 for x8 and 8.8 for x16).

Some words on the implementation:
I don't think it was said in class that std::vectors are not really supported.
However, I still used them to allocate the memory, since allocating x16 on the stack will crash, and I do not want to use malloc.
I also replaced the bool type in the solid vector for unsigned char, since bool vectors are fake, and I think the data() pointer would reflect it.
